    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Verbena peruviana improperly include inducing vomiting due to the plant's toxic nature, which can cause gastrointestinal irritation and potentially lead to dehydration and electrolyte imbalances. Experiencing allergic reactions, such as hives and itchy skin, is also a possibility, as Verbena peruviana contains compounds that can trigger immune responses in susceptible individuals. Furthermore, improperly using Verbena peruviana can exacerbate existing allergies, particularly those related to ragweed and other plants in the Verbenaceae family. Additionally, Verbena peruviana can cause nausea and stomach upset due to its irritating properties and potential for contaminating food and water sources. These side effects can be attributed to the plant's high concentration of volatile oils and other bioactive compounds that can have adverse effects on the human body when used improperly.",
    "uses": "Verbena peruviana is traditionally used in folk medicine to treat various health conditions. It has been reported to have anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial properties, which may aid in wound healing and reducing infections. The plant is also said to have antispasmodic effects, making it useful for relieving muscle cramps and spasms. In some cultures, Verbena peruviana is used to treat fever, cough, and respiratory issues. Further research is needed to confirm the efficacy and safety of using Verbena peruviana for medicinal purposes.",
    "taxonomy": "Verbena peruviana is classified within the family Verbenaceae, a group of flowering plants native to the Americas. This classification is based on its botanical characteristics and evolutionary relationships with other plants in the Verbenaceae family. Verbena peruviana is further classified within the genus Verbena, which comprises a diverse group of plants commonly known as vervains. The genus Verbena is divided into several species, with Verbena peruviana being one of the many species within this group. The exact classification of Verbena peruviana may vary depending on the source and the most recent taxonomic research.",
    "benefits": "Verbena peruviana, also known as the Peruvian verbena, is a plant with a long history of traditional use in medicine and herbalism. Its leaves and flowers have been used to treat various health issues, including fever, cough, and digestive problems. The plant is said to have anti-inflammatory properties, which may help reduce swelling and alleviate pain. Additionally, Verbena peruviana is believed to have antimicrobial properties, which can help combat infections and promote wound healing. Further research is needed to confirm the full range of health benefits associated with this plant.",
    "parts": "Verbena peruviana is primarily used in traditional medicine, and its medicinal properties are found in various parts of the plant. The leaves of Verbena peruviana are reported to have antioxidant and anti-inflammatory effects, which contribute to their medicinal value. Additionally, the plant's flowers and stems are also used in folk medicine for their potential health benefits. However, the specific parts used for medicinal purposes may vary depending on the region and cultural practices. More research is needed to fully understand the medicinal properties and applications of Verbena peruviana.",
    "intro": "Verbena peruviana, also known as Lippia or Verbena, is a perennial herb native to the Andean region, belonging to the Verbenaceae family. The plant has been traditionally used for its medicinal properties, offering relief from anxiety, insomnia, and digestive issues due to its adaptogenic and anti-inflammatory effects. The bioactive constituents of Verbena peruviana include volatile oils, flavonoids, and phenolic acids, which contribute to its therapeutic properties. In herbal medicine, Verbena peruviana is commonly prepared as a tea, tincture, or infusion, often combined with other herbs to enhance its benefits, particularly for anxiety and stress relief."
